76561198074672567,Not Recommended,298520,24401704,"Posted: 18 July, 2016",all,Ang3lusmortis,"Just plain and simple, this isn't a particularly fun game as far as I'm concerned.  The concept is great; mechs in some sort of 2D space-theme shoot-em-up with massive stellar bodies and varying gravity, but throwing in non-optional and timed ""orbital trials"" just to unlock weaponry is annoying...The Best:- High quality backgrounds, backdrops, and environments (sort of a must-have for any 2D platformer style games these days).  If the trials weren't timed, I'd probably appreciate these graphics even more...- Sky is the limit (or space) as far as ""how good you can get"" is concerned; get comfortable with how the gravity works, how to move around, and be able to switch weapons when needed, but reaction-timing and coordination are serious game changers.The Good:- not terrible digital/techno style soundtracks- challenging fast-paced gameplay- rather challenging movement (in order to complete trials in a timely manner or be reasonably competitive in multiplayer, you'll have to be able to sling-shot around stellar bodies to get to some locations)The Bad:- TIMED TRIALS: you HAVE to follow the progression to be able to unlock each subsequent weapon, regardless of preferences in playstyle- Hit boxes: time and again, thought you just hit that enemy?  Well, it sure as hell hit you.- Lots of different ""Gravitational Bodies,"" but none of them labeled or any inkling of the effect they will have on your or your weapons.The Ugly:- At least on PC/Mac, the keyboard controls are very difficult to get comfortable with; you can hold down the left or right arrow key and start running around a planetary body, but go to jump off or use a thruster and the arrow key held down still dictates your direction (even if you've run around to the opposite side)- No apparent variation in the stats of the mechs to fit different playstyles (slow and tanky, bruiser, fast but weak, etc.)- Timed trials are exactly the same each time; no variation in enemy behavior asside from scripts relating to player position means all you really have to do is get familiar with the layout and weapon characteristics and play a level over and over until earning 3 stars.Overall:As far as controls are concerned, I'd like to atleast have the option to keep the player ""upright"" constantly, and rotate the screen as you move; otherwise my personal opinion is that you HAVE to have a controller with an 8-direction pad for the movement to ever really feel natural, and a monitor refresh of at least 120hz.  Otherwise, as many would agree, if you're looking for a fast-paced, intense, and dynamic 2D game, Orbital Gear is probably for you.  If you get irritated easily when gameplay isn't particularly intuitive and you don't care for timed-trials (like myself) then Orbital Gear isn't.  If you can get past the timed trials, the multiplayer can be a lot of fun, as long as there are enough people online..."
