,Recommended,298520,34067336,Posted: 6 August,all,Al-Crypt.zu],Very good game ^^
,Not Recommended,298520,34362034,Posted: 19 August,all,I Solve Problems,"It's surprising to me how this game is no longer an Early Access title. Ultimately, Orbital Gear just doesn't deliver that feeling of ""like your first rocket jump in quake"" as impressed by the trailer. Why? Because there are a few game-breaking issues that, while not game crashes from bad code or glitches, still kill what would otherwise be an enjoyable ""timewaster"" game.Controls. Let's put it like this: Orbital gear is basically a console game that the dev's can't afford to create exclusively for consoles. any type of keyboard/mouse layout is clunky, inefficient, and ultimately frustrating to use because the game mechanics lean so far towards controller use that it alienates any gamer confortable with the good 'ol WASD.Controller Support. You'd think Orbital Gear, with its controller-based menu graphics and emphasis on controller gameplay, would actually tell you what sort of controller is supported, or would even detect the fact that you're using a controller... Nope! So far, controller support for Orbital is down to groping in the dark for some elusive configuration that might actually make controller gameplay feasable.UI/Graphics. Yes, Orbital Gear has stunning landscape graphics. However, the UI is too small to properly navigate at times. In addition, the most important features of a graphical UI (some buttons, THE CURSOR YOU USE TO SHOOT AT ENEMIES) are often rendered to be near-inconspicuous, a deadly flaw during even a caricature of battle.singleplayer ""training..."" This is one of those games where the developers decided that, instead of giving customers an actual usable singleplayer experience, they could just foist a series of ""training"" time trials on buyers to somehow satisfy the singleplayer gamers' outcries. There are no bots, no real tutorials, firing ranges... Heck, there isn't even some sort of ""campaign"" to introduce players to the many varied weapons and gadgets, which even with the corniest, shallowest storyline would do much better at training players for online combat than the current ""feature"" of time trials.Ultimately, Orbital gear, while a semi-intriguing gameplay experiment, is not worth the $10 ($9.99) to buy it. Sure, get it on sale, accept it as a gift from someone, but until the developers improve the positively minor yet gamebreaking flaws of this timestealer, your money, steam funds, or credit is put to better use in your wallet."
